  <h1>WARN Act Severance: What You're Owed When Laid Off</h1>
  <p class="byline">By <strong>Blake Anders</strong>, Paralegal (employment). Reviewed by Sloan Whitfield, SHRM-CP. Updated May 2026.</p>

  <p>
    Most employees who are laid off without much warning assume that's simply how layoffs work. Sometimes it is. But when a layoff meets certain size thresholds, federal law may require your employer to have given you 60 days' advance notice — and if they didn't, you may be owed back pay and benefits for up to 60 days, regardless of any separate severance offer.
  </p>

  <h2>What Is the WARN Act?</h2>
  <p>
    The Worker Adjustment and Retraining Notification Act (WARN Act), enacted in 1988, requires covered employers to provide advance notice of mass layoffs and plant closings so that affected workers and communities have time to prepare. The Act is enforced through civil lawsuits filed in federal district court — there's no federal agency that investigates WARN Act violations proactively, so the burden is on affected workers (or their attorneys) to pursue claims.
  </p>

  <h2>Who Is Covered: The 100-Employee Threshold</h2>
  <p>
    The federal WARN Act applies to employers with <strong>100 or more full-time employees</strong> (or 100 or more employees who in the aggregate work at least 4,000 hours per week, excluding overtime). Part-time employees (those working fewer than 20 hours per week or employed for fewer than 6 of the last 12 months) do not count toward the threshold and are generally not protected by the federal WARN Act, though some state laws differ.
  </p>
  <p>
    Employers below the 100-employee threshold — including most small businesses — are not subject to the federal WARN Act. However, several states have their own WARN-equivalent statutes with lower thresholds (see "State Mini-WARN Acts" below).
  </p>

  <h2>When Is Notice Required?</h2>
  <p>
    The federal WARN Act requires 60 calendar days' advance written notice in two specific situations:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Plant closing:</strong> A permanent or temporary shutdown of a single employment site — or one or more operating units within a site — that affects 50 or more full-time employees during any 30-day period.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Mass layoff:</strong> A reduction in force at a single employment site that affects either (a) 500 or more full-time employees during any 30-day period, or (b) 50–499 full-time employees who represent at least 33% of the total active workforce at that site during any 30-day period.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Notice must be given to: (1) each affected employee (or their union representative), (2) the state's dislocated worker unit, and (3) the chief elected official of the local government where the layoff occurs.
  </p>

  <h2>What Are You Owed If Notice Wasn't Given?</h2>
  <p>
    If a covered employer fails to provide the required 60 days' notice, affected employees are entitled to:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Back pay:</strong> Wages and benefits for each day of the violation, up to a maximum of 60 days. If the employer gave 30 days' notice but was required to give 60, the back pay covers the missing 30 days.</li>
    <li><strong>Benefits continuation:</strong> The value of medical expenses that would have been covered under your health plan during the violation period.</li>
    <li><strong>Employer ERISA liability:</strong> Any pension contributions that would have vested during the notice period that didn't, due to the employer's failure to provide proper notice.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Back pay is calculated at the employee's regular rate of compensation, including the cost of any benefits provided during that period. This is separate from — and in addition to — any voluntary severance the employer offers. A well-crafted separation agreement from your employer may include language waiving WARN Act claims, which is one more reason to have an attorney review your agreement before signing.
  </p>

  <h2>Exceptions to the 60-Day Requirement</h2>
  <p>
    The WARN Act includes three narrow exceptions that allow employers to provide less than 60 days' notice without incurring full liability:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Faltering company:</strong> The employer was actively seeking capital or business to avoid the closing, and providing notice would have jeopardized that effort. This exception is narrowly interpreted by courts.</li>
    <li><strong>Unforeseeable business circumstances:</strong> The layoff was caused by a sudden, dramatic, and unexpected business circumstance — such as the abrupt loss of a major client or an unexpected order cancellation — that the employer could not have reasonably foreseen. The COVID-19 pandemic, for example, generated significant litigation over this exception.</li>
    <li><strong>Natural disaster:</strong> The layoff was a direct result of a flood, earthquake, drought, storm, tidal wave, or similar natural disaster.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Even when an exception applies, the employer must give as much notice as practicable and explain in writing why the exception applies. Employers sometimes invoke these exceptions incorrectly — if you believe your employer's claimed exception is a stretch, an employment attorney can assess the strength of a WARN Act claim.
  </p>

  <h2>State Mini-WARN Acts</h2>
  <p>
    Several states have enacted their own WARN-equivalent laws with broader coverage than the federal statute. Key differences often include lower employee thresholds and longer notice periods:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>California:</strong> Applies to employers with 75+ employees; covers layoffs of 50+ workers at a single location in a 30-day period (no 33% threshold). Also applies to part-time workers.</li>
    <li><strong>New York:</strong> Applies to employers with 50+ full-time employees; covers layoffs of 25+ workers at a single site representing at least 33% of the workforce, or 250+ workers.</li>
    <li><strong>New Jersey:</strong> Applies to employers with 100+ full-time employees; 60 days' notice required; also requires severance pay of one week per year of service if proper notice isn't given.</li>
    <li><strong>Illinois:</strong> Applies to employers with 75+ full-time employees; covers layoffs of 25+ workers representing at least 33% of the workforce, or 250+ workers.</li>
    <li><strong>Massachusetts:</strong> Broader "plant closing" law requiring advance notice, with some severance provisions.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If you were laid off in a state with a mini-WARN law and your employer had 50+ employees, it's worth a quick attorney consultation to check whether state-level back pay rights apply even if you don't meet the federal 100-employee threshold.
  </p>

  <h2>How to Pursue a WARN Act Claim</h2>
  <p>
    WARN Act claims are filed as civil lawsuits in federal district court. There is no administrative charge process (unlike with the EEOC). The statute of limitations is generally three years from the date of violation, though courts apply varying statutes.
  </p>
  <p>
    Because WARN Act cases often involve multiple affected employees, they are frequently brought as class actions — which means an attorney may take the case on a contingency basis if the violation is clear and the class is sizable. If you were part of a mass layoff and believe the WARN Act was violated, contact an employment attorney promptly, as other affected employees may already be organizing a claim.
  </p>

  <p class="disclaimer">
    This guide is for informational purposes only. It does not constitute legal advice. WARN Act applicability and remedies vary depending on employer size, circumstances, and applicable state law. Consult a licensed employment attorney if you believe your rights under the WARN Act may have been violated.
  </p>
